My stomach also began to roar and, tired of the stale bread and salty water I could conjure, I decided to venture into and inn to purchase adequate provisions.  As I pushed through the straw door of the inn, the scent of death and disease waft through the air and into my nostrils and mouth.  I grew sick, but persisted to find the source of this filth.  I headed towards the back of the inn, and found an ill gnome slouched in the corner, with a green mucus running from the corners of his mouth and eyes.  He donned an oracle robe along with a finely crafted staff, but from the lack of wrinkles of his face, I noted he could be no older than 40, a mere child to a gnome.  He reached for me with a frail arm, and I reluctantly came to his side, fearing my own health.  He tried to talk, but his body was weak, and a thick yellow liquid oozed from his bottom lip.  I began to cry, because I knew that it was even too late for an Oracle to cure my fallen brother.<br>
'Who did this to you!' I screamed while grabbing his shoulder.  I could feel his skin deteriorating underneath his robe; his flesh felt like rotten fruit.  I quickly withdrew my hand in fear of causing further damage.  A crust enveloped his eyes, and he was squinting to make out my face.  Focusing his remaining strength, he swung his head back against the wall, and gasped for air a few times.  Then started to softly whisper, 'Aar... Aarat... Aarathin did this... to me...' and with that, his jawbone dislocated from his skull.  He desperately gagged for oxygen as his body started to decompose.  I could hear his bones and organs surrendering to the pressure of his own weight, and watched in horror as his body turned into a lifeless lump of flesh, blood and shattered bones.<br>
I hastely left the inn.  Aarathin.  Aarathin.  The name danced in my head.  I conjured thoughts of the appearance of this necromancer, and a pain filled my heart.  I continued on with a fire in my soul, to find this warlock named Aarathin...<br>
